        <headline>Special Weather Statement issued July 17 at 2:59PM EDT by NWS Charleston WV</headline>
        <description>At 257 PM EDT, Doppler radar was tracking strong thunderstorms along
a line extending from near Clendenin to near Julian. Movement was
east at 30 mph.

HAZARD...Wind gusts up to 40 mph and pea size hail.

SOURCE...Radar indicated.

IMPACT...Gusty winds could knock down tree limbs and blow around
unsecured objects. Minor hail damage to vegetation is
possible.

Locations impacted include...
Madison, Clay, Montgomery, Chesapeake, Marmet, Ansted, Belle, Cedar
Grove, East Bank, Glasgow, Smithers, Gauley Bridge, Pratt, Powellton,
Glen, Coal Fork, Birch River, Burnwell, Harrison, and Danville.

This includes the following highways...
West Virginia Turnpike between mile markers 63 and 93.
Route 119 between mile markers 49 and 53.
Route 19 between mile markers 46 and 61.
</description>
        <instruction>If outdoors, consider seeking shelter inside a building.

Torrential rainfall is also occurring with these storms and may lead
to localized flooding. Do not drive your vehicle through flooded
roadways.

Frequent cloud to ground lightning is occurring with these storms.
Lightning can strike 10 miles away from a thunderstorm. Seek a safe
shelter inside a building or vehicle.</instruction>
